<subSubSection pageId="184" pageNumber="185" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="184.[189,310,1161,1187]" box="[189,310,1161,1187]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1161,1187]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1161,1187]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="184.[189,1399,1208,1451]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Ophiacanthid with small to moderately large LAPs of thick, massive and generally bulging aspect; outer surface devoid of conspicuous ornament; no spurs on outer proximal and inner distal edges; small, earshaped spine articulations freestanding or in shallow depressions of bulging distal portion of LAP; spine articulations commonly tilted; ventral lobe rugged to irregularly corrugate, commonly confluent with outer surface stereom; spine articulations not sharply bordered proximally and with dorsalward increase in size; short, broad, dorso-proximalwards bent, tongue-shaped ridge devoid of kinks or widened parts; tentacle notch very small, poorly defined.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="185" lastPageNumber="186" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="184.[189,303,1491,1517]" box="[189,303,1491,1517]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1491,1517]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1491,1517]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="184.[189,1399,1538,1745]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2011" box="[189,519,1538,1564]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Inexpectacantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="acrobatica">
<emphasis box="[189,519,1538,1564]" italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Inexpectacantha acrobatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably one of the best-known fossil ophiuroids. In fact, the original description was based on outstandingly well-preserved material from the Pliensbachian of 
<collectingCountry box="[1311,1394,1575,1601]" name="France" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">France</collectingCountry>
, comprising both articulated skeletons and dissociated skeletal parts, including LAPs, allowing for a morphological analysis of exceptional detail (Thuy 2011).As a result, fossil dissociated LAPs compatible with the LAP morphological diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2011" box="[707,901,1682,1708]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Inexpectacantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[707,901,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Inexpectacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unambiguously identifiable and thus provide evidence for bracketing the divergence time of the genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="184.[189,1399,1784,2027]" lastBlockId="185.[189,1399,267,329]" lastPageId="185" lastPageNumber="186" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">
The LAPs of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2011" box="[348,542,1785,1811]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Inexpectacantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[348,542,1785,1811]" italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Inexpectacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are among the most characteristic of all ophiacanthid LAP 
<typeStatus box="[1239,1305,1785,1811]" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">types</typeStatus>
. In fact, the a massive, thick, round and bulging general aspect, the lack of conspicuous outer surface ornament and spurs on the outer proximal and inner distal edges, small spine articulations with dorsalward increase in size and not bordered proximally by a ridge, a large, broad, tongue-shaped ridge devoid of kinks, extensions or strongly widened parts on the inner side, and very small, poorly defined tentacle notches are a combination of characters not found in any other ophiacanthid genus. Superficial similarities are shared with the LAPs of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lyman, 1869" authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1869" box="[396,742,2001,2027]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiochondrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="184" pageNumber="185" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[396,579,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="184" pageNumber="185">Ophiochondrus</emphasis>
Lyman, 1869
</taxonomicName>
, in which, however, the spine articulations are generally not oblique and not confluent with the outer surface stereom. In addition, the LAPs of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lyman" authorityYear="1869" box="[1216,1399,267,293]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiochondrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1216,1399,267,293]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">Ophiochondrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are less massive, and the ridge on the inner side displays a ventro-proximalwards projecting extension.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="185.[189,1399,368,606]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">
Greatest similarities are shared with the LAPs of 
<taxonomicName authority="Thuy, 2013" authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[800,983,368,394]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophioleviathan" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[800,983,368,394]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">Ophioleviathan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[994,1105,368,395]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(see below), particularly with respect to the massive and thick general aspect, and the shape of the spine articulations and of the ridge on the inner side. The LAPs of 
<taxonomicName authority="Thuy, 2013" authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[639,822,438,464]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophioleviathan" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[639,822,438,464]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">Ophioleviathan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[831,942,439,465]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, however, are significantly larger than those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2011" box="[299,493,474,500]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Inexpectacantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[299,493,474,500]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">Inexpectacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and display larger, near-vertical spine articulations in deeper notches and composed of distal and proximal rather than dorsal and ventral lobes, with a strongly thickened distal lobe. Nevertheless, as discussed below, the LAP morphologies of both genera as so similar that they most likely represent sister taxa.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="185.[189,1399,645,882]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">
Interestingly, the currently known species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2011" box="[721,915,645,671]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Inexpectacantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[721,915,645,671]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">Inexpectacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fall into two groups on the basis of LAP morphology: 
<taxonomicName authority="Thuy, 2013" authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[350,431,681,706]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Inexpectacantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ritae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[350,431,681,706]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">I. ritae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[440,533,680,706]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hess, 1962)" authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName="Hess" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[593,866,680,707]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Inexpectacantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="lunaris">
<emphasis box="[593,702,680,706]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">I. lunaris</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hess H." box="[719,857,680,707]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" pagination="609 - 656" refId="ref122260" refString="Hess H. 1962. Mikropalaontologische Untersuchungen an Ophiuren II: Die Ophiuren aus dem Lias (Pliensbachien-Toarcien) von Seewen (Kt. Solothurn). Eclogae geologicae Helvetiae 55: 609 - 656." type="journal article" year="1962">Hess, 1962</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, plus 
<taxonomicName authority="Thuy, 2013" authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[937,1023,681,706]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Inexpectacantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="weisi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[937,1023,681,706]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">I. weisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1032,1125,680,706]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2011" box="[1185,1337,680,706]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Inexpectacantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="acrobatica">
<emphasis box="[1185,1337,680,706]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">I. acrobatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The two last named are characterised by generally smaller LAPs with smaller height/width ratios, spine articulations freestanding rather than in notches, a more coarsely meshed stereom on the outer surface, and lip-shaped distal knobs in the spine articulations of the distal LAPs. Most of these characters are typically indicative of a paedomorphic condition (
<bibRefCitation author="Stohr S." box="[777,912,820,847]" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" pagination="543 - 576" refId="ref128037" refString="Stohr S. 2005. Who's who among baby brittle stars (Echinodermata, Ophiuroidea): postmetamorphic development of some North Atlantic forms. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 143 (4): 543 - 576. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2005.00155. x" type="journal article" year="2005">St√∂hr 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 2011). Indeed, the articulated specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2011" box="[221,548,856,882]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Inexpectacantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="185" pageNumber="186" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="acrobatica">
<emphasis box="[221,548,856,882]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="186">Inexpectacantha acrobatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
display a strikingly paedomorphic general morphology (Thuy 2011).
</paragraph>
